<section xml:id="subsec-surface-area-of-prisms" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Surface Area of Prisms</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.7 Surface Area
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p>
                        Determine the surface area of prisms, pyramids, cones, frustums and spheres
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            <p component="lesson-plan">
                <p> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Understand the definition of a prism, the meaning of surface area, and how nets relate to the faces of a prism.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Apply the formula <m>\text{Surface Area} = 2F + Pl</m> to calculate the surface area of various prisms.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Solve real-life problems involving the surface area of prisms, including cost and material estimation.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <ul>
            <li>Determine the surface area of prisms, pyramids, cones, frustums and spheres</li>
            <li>Explore the use of the surface area and volume of solids in real-life situations</li>
        </ul>
    </objectives>
    <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/surface-area/surface-area-of-prisms.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/surface-area/step-by-step-guide_surface-area-of-prisms.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />



    <p>
        A <term>prism</term> is a three-dimensional solid made of two identical faces called <term>faces</term>, and connected by rectangular faces. Triangular prisms, cylinders, and cuboids are examples of prisms. The surface area of a prism can be found by calculating the area of each face and adding them to the area of the faces.
    </p>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    Students work in groups to discover surface area by creating nets, measuring faces, and adding all face areas together.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Teacher's Role</title>
            <p>
                Circulate among groups and ask probing questions such as:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li><p>How many faces does your object have?</p></li>
                <li><p>Are all the faces the same size?</p></li>
                <li><p>How can you check if you've counted all the faces?</p></li>
            </ul>
            <p>
                Listen for student discoveries about the relationship between dimensions and surface area. Use their solutions to bridge to formal instruction in Phase 2.
            </p>
        </paragraphs>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Discussion Prompts</title>
            <ul>
                <li><p>What will happen if the surface area doubles in size?</p></li>
                <li><p>Why do bigger prisms have more surface area?</p></li>
                <li><p>How does the perimeter of the face relate to the lateral area?</p></li>
            </ul>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <term>Work in groups:</term> Form groups of <m>2</m> or <m>3</m> students.
            </p>
            <p>
                <term>Materials Needed:</term>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Pen or pencil
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Grid/graph paper or plain paper
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Rulers
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Pre-made nets of triangular prisms (optional)
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <p>
                <term>Instructions:</term>
            </p>

            <sidebyside widths="45% 45%" valign="middle">
                <image>
                    <latex-image label="triangular-prism-solid">
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1, every node/.style={scale=0.8}]
                            % prism vertices
                            \coordinate (A) at (0,0,0);
                            \coordinate (B) at (3,0,0);
                            \coordinate (C) at (1.5,4,0); % Increased height for 10cm scale
                            \coordinate (D) at (0,0,4);
                            \coordinate (E) at (3,0,4);
                            \coordinate (F) at (1.5,4,4);

                            % faces (Rear)
                            \draw[-] (A)--(B)--(C)--cycle;
                            
                            % Connecting edges
                            \draw (A)--(D) node[midway, left, sloped] {9 cm};
                            \draw (B)--(E);
                            \draw (C)--(F);
                            
                            % Front face
                            \draw[thick] (D)--(E)--(F)--cycle;

                            % Measurements on the front triangular face
                            % face label
                            \draw[-] (0,-0.3,4) -- (3,-0.3,4) node[midway, below] {8 cm};
                            % Height dashed line
                            \draw[dashed] (1.5,0,4) -- (1.5,4,4) node[midway, right] {10 cm};
                            % Right angle marker
                            \draw (1.5,0.2,4) -- (1.7,0.2,4) -- (1.7,0,4);
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>

                <image>
                    <latex-image label="triangular-prism-net">
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.6, every node/.style={scale=0.8}]
                            % Main rectangular body
                            \draw (0,0) rectangle (8,4);
                            % Triangular flaps
                            \draw (0,4) -- (4,7) -- (8,4);
                            \draw (0,0) -- (4,-3) -- (8,0);

                            % Labels
                            \node[left] at (0,2) {Length ($l$)};
                            \node[below] at (4,0) {Base ($b$)};
                            \draw[dashed] (4,4) -- (4,7) node[midway, right] {Height ($h$)};
                            
                            % Optional: width of the side rectangles
                            % \node[above] at (2,4.5) {side}; 
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </sidebyside>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            In your group, draw a triangular prism and its net on paper.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Label the dimensions of the triangular face and the length of the prism.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Calculate the area of the triangular face.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Calculate the perimeter of the triangular face.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Multiplying the perimeter of the face by the length of the prism to get the lateral area.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Add the areas of the two triangular faces and the lateral area.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <p>
                A triangular prism has two identical triangular faces and three rectangular faces.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>
     <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formalize the general prism surface area formula <m>\text{S.A.} = 2F + Pl</m> and connect student discoveries to the formal formula.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Scaffolding Strategies</title>
            <ul>
                <li><p>Address misconceptions revealed during the anchor task, such as confusing perimeter with area or forgetting to count all faces.</p></li>
                <li><p>Use visual diagrams to show how nets unfold into 3D shapes.</p></li>
                <li><p>Emphasize that surface area is measured in square units (<m>\text{cm}^2</m>, <m>\text{m}^2</m>).</p></li>
                <li><p>Connect student discoveries from the activity to the formal formula.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </paragraphs>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Common Misconceptions</title>
            <ul>
                <li><p>Confusing surface area with volume.</p></li>
                <li><p>Forgetting to count all faces (especially the two end faces).</p></li>
                <li><p>Using linear units instead of square units.</p></li>
                <li><p>Confusing perimeter with area when calculating lateral surface area.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>
    <insight>
        <p>
            A <m>\textbf{prism}</m> is a geometric object with two identical, parallel faces and straight sides connecting them. These include rectangular prisms, triangular prisms, and pentagonal prisms (which is shown)
        </p>
        <p>
            <image>
                <latex-image label="pentagonal-prism">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=3]
                        % Back pentagon
                        \coordinate (A) at (0,1);
                        \coordinate (B) at (0.95,0.31);
                        \coordinate (C) at (0.59,-0.81);
                        \coordinate (D) at (-0.59,-0.81);
                        \coordinate (E) at (-0.95,0.31);
                        \fill[gray!20] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- (D) -- (E) -- cycle;
                        \draw[thick] (A)--(B)--(C)--(D)--(E)--cycle;
                        % Front pentagon (shifted)
                        \coordinate (A1) at (2,0.2);
                        \coordinate (B1) at (2.95,-0.49);
                        \coordinate (C1) at (2.59,-1.81);
                        \coordinate (D1) at (1.41,-1.81);
                        \coordinate (E1) at (1.05,-0.49);
                        % Side faces (light blue, fairly opaque)
                        \fill[blue!30,opacity=0.9] (A) -- (B) -- (B1) -- (A1) -- cycle;
                        \fill[blue!30,opacity=0.9] (B) -- (C) -- (C1) -- (B1) -- cycle;
                        \fill[blue!30,opacity=0.9] (C) -- (D) -- (D1) -- (C1) -- cycle;
                        \fill[blue!30,opacity=0.9] (D) -- (E) -- (E1) -- (D1) -- cycle;
                        \fill[blue!30,opacity=0.9] (E) -- (A) -- (A1) -- (E1) -- cycle;
                        \fill[gray!10] (A1) -- (B1) -- (C1) -- (D1) -- (E1) -- cycle;
                        \draw[thick] (A1)--(B1)--(C1)--(D1)--(E1)--cycle;
                        % Connecting edges
                        \draw (A)-- node[midway, above right] {Length $l$} (A1) (D)--(D1) (E)--(E1);
                        \draw[dashed] (B)--(B1) (C)--(C1);
                        \draw[dashed] (A)--(B)--(C)--(D);
                        % Labels
                        \node at (2.00,-0.96) {Face $F$};
                        \node[below] at ($(C1)!0.5!(D1)$) {Perimeter $P$};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </p>
        <p>
            To calculate the surface area of a prisms, we use the formula:
            <md>
                <mrow> \text{Surface Area} \amp = 2\times \text{Area of Face} + \text{Perimeter of Face} \times \text{Length} </mrow>
                <mrow> \amp = 2F + Pl </mrow>
            </md>
            where <m>F</m> is the area of the face, <m>P</m> is the perimeter of the face, and <m>l</m> is length of the prism.
        </p>
        <p>
            This works for any prism, including rectangular prisms (see <xref ref="subsec-surface-area-of-cubes-and-cuboids"/>), triangular prisms, and cylinders (see <xref ref="subsec-surface-area-of-cylinders"/>)
        </p>
        <p>
            In the special case of a <term>triangular prisms</term>, we have <m>F = \frac{1}{2} \times b \times h</m> where <m>b</m> is the base of the triangle and <m>h</m> is the height of the triangle. The perimeter <m>P</m> is the sum of the three sides of the triangle.
        </p>
        
    </insight>

