    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Assessment</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    3 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formatively assess individual learner understanding of prism surface area.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Learning Experience</title>
                <p>
                    Learners independently complete a short assessment task (select from the exercises below).
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Collect and review the exit tickets to gauge learner understanding and identify any common misconceptions that need to be addressed in the next lesson.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Exit Ticket Questions (Teacher Reference)</title>
            <p>
                <ol marker="1.">
                    <li>
                        <p>A cube has side length 9 cm. Find its total surface area. <alert>Answer:</alert> <m>6 \times 9^2 = 486 \, \text{cm}^2</m></p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>A rectangular box measures 12 cm by 7 cm by 5 cm. Calculate its total surface area. <alert>Answer:</alert> <m>2(12 \times 7 + 12 \times 5 + 7 \times 5) = 2(84 + 60 + 35) = 358 \, \text{cm}^2</m></p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>A cuboid-shaped water tank measures 4 m by 3 m by 2 m. Only the four walls and the base are painted. Find the area painted. <alert>Answer:</alert> <m>2(4 \times 2) + 2(3 \times 2) + (4 \times 3) = 16 + 12 + 12 = 40 \, \text{m}^2</m></p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </paragraphs>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Assessment Criteria</title>
            <ul>
                <li><p>Correct identification of shape type (cube vs. cuboid vs. general prism)</p></li>
                <li><p>Proper formula selection</p></li>
                <li><p>Accurate calculation of face areas</p></li>
                <li><p>Correct addition of all face areas</p></li>
                <li><p>Appropriate use of square units</p></li>
            </ul>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

    <!-- <xi:include href="../../resources-checkpoint.ptx" /> -->

    <exercises xml:id="exercises-triangular-prism-surface-area">
        <!-- Level 1: Simple formula applications -->

        <!-- Level 2: Direct prism formula uses -->
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A pentagonal prism has a pentagonal face with area <m>54 \, \text{cm}^2</m> and perimeter <m>30 \, \text{cm}</m>. The length of the prism is <m>10 \, \text{cm}</m>. Find the total surface area.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    We have <m>\text{Surface Area} = 2F + Pl </m>. Given <m>F = 54 \, \text{cm}^2</m>, <m>P = 30 \, \text{cm}</m>, <m>l = 10 \, \text{cm}</m>:
                </p>
                <p>
                    Lateral area: <me>Pl = 30 \times 10 = 300 \, \text{cm}^2</me>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Two faces: <me>2F = 2 \times 54 = 108 \, \text{cm}^2</me>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Total surface area: <me>2F + Pl = 108 + 300 = 408 \, \text{cm}^2</me>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <!-- Level 3: Triangular prism standard applications -->

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A triangular prism has a triangular face of base <m>10 \text{cm}</m> and height <m>6 \text{cm}</m>. The two equal sides of the triangle are <m>8 \text{cm}</m> each. The length of the prism is <m>15 \text{cm}</m>. Find its total surface area.
                </p >
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Interpreting the triangular face as base <m>b=10\,\text{cm}</m> and triangle height <m>h=6\,\text{cm}</m> with equal sides <m>8\,\text{cm}</m> and prism length <m>l=15\,\text{cm}</m>:
                </p>
                <p>
                    Area of triangular face: <me>F = \tfrac{1}{2}bh = \tfrac{1}{2}\times10\times6 = 30 \, \text{cm}^2</me>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Perimeter: <me>P = 10 + 8 + 8 = 26 \, \text{cm}</me>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Lateral area: <me>Pl = 26 \times 15 = 390 \, \text{cm}^2</me>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Total surface area: <me>2F + Pl = 2\times30 + 390 = 60 + 390 = 450 \, \text{cm}^2</me>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A triangular tent is shaped like a triangular prism. The triangular face has base <m>8 \text{m}</m> and height <m>3 \text{m}</m>. The slant sides are <m>5 \text{m}</m> each. The length of the tent is <m>6 \text{m}</m>. Find the total surface area of the tent canvas (including the two triangular ends).
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Area of triangular face: <me>F = \tfrac{1}{2} \times 8 \times 3 = 12 \, \text{m}^2</me>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Perimeter of triangular face: <me>P = 8 + 5 + 5 = 18 \, \text{m}</me>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Lateral area: <me>Pl = 18 \times 6 = 108 \, \text{m}^2</me>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Total surface area: <me>2F + Pl = 2\times12 + 108 = 24 + 108 = 132 \, \text{m}^2</me>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <!-- Level 4: Multi-step / Heron -->

                <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A triangular prism has a triangular face with base <m>10 \, \text{cm}</m> and height <m>12 \, \text{cm}</m>. The two remaining sides of the face are equal. The length of the prism is <m>15 \, \text{cm}</m>. Find its total surface area.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Area of triangular face: <m>F = \tfrac{1}{2}bh = \tfrac{1}{2}\times 10 \times 6 = 30 \, \text{cm}^2</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    For the perimeter, since the triangle is isoceles the vertical <m>h</m> bisects the base. So we can calculate the other side lengths <m>x</m> using Pythagoras' theorem: <m>x = \sqrt{12^2 + 5^2} = 13 \, \text{cm}</m>. So <m>P = 10 + 13 + 13 = 36 \, \text{cm}</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Lateral area: <m>Pl = 36 \times 15 = 540 \, \text{cm}^2</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Total surface area: <m>2F + Pl = 2\times 30 + 540 = 60 + 540 = 600 \, \text{cm}^2</m>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A bridge support structure has the shape of a triangular prism, with a face measuring <m>10 \, \text{m}</m>, <m>17 \, \text{m}</m>, and <m>21 \, \text{m}</m>, and a length of <m>50 \, \text{m}</m>. If paint costs <m>300</m> Ksh per square metre, how much will it cost to paint the entire surface area of the support structure?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Surface Area = 2F + Pl. Compute using Heron's formula for the triangular face with sides 10 m, 17 m and 21 m, and prism length <m>l=50\,\text{m}</m>:
                </p>
                <p>
                    Semi-perimeter: <me>s = \frac{10 + 17 + 21}{2} = 24 \, \text{m}</me>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Area of triangular face: 
                    <md>
                        <mrow>F \amp = \sqrt{s(s-10)(s-17)(s-21)} </mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = \sqrt{24\times14\times7\times3} </mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = \sqrt{7056} </mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = 84 \, \text{m}^2</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Perimeter: <me>P = 10 + 17 + 21 = 48 \, \text{m}</me>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Lateral area: <me>Pl = 48 \times 50 = 2400 \, \text{m}^2</me>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Total surface area: <me>2F + Pl = 2\times84 + 2400 = 168 + 2400 = 2568 \, \text{m}^2</me>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Thus the total cost is <me>2568 \, \text{m}^2 \times 300 \, \text{Ksh/m}^2 = 770400 \, \text{Ksh}</me>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
                        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A regular hexagonal prism has a hexagonal face with side <m>6 \, \text{cm}</m>. The length of the prism is <m>10 \, \text{cm}</m>.
                </p>
                <image>
                    <latex-image label="hexagonal-prism-diagram">
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.0, every node/.style={scale=0.9}]
                            % Draw back hexagon (shifted)
                            \coordinate (A) at (0:1);
                            \foreach \i in {0,60,...,300} { \coordinate (B\i) at ({cos(\i)*1},{sin(\i)*1}); }
                            % front hexagon shifted right
                            \begin{scope}[xshift=3cm, yshift=-1cm]
                                \foreach \i in {0,60,...,300} { \coordinate (C\i) at ({cos(\i)*1},{sin(\i)*1}); }
                            \end{scope}
                            % draw hexagons
                            \draw[thick,fill=gray!10] (C0) -- (C60) -- (C120) -- (C180) -- (C240) -- (C300) -- cycle;
                            \draw[thick] (B0) -- (B60) -- (B120) -- (B180) -- (B240) -- (B300) -- cycle;
                            % connect corresponding vertices
                            \foreach \i/\j in {0/0,60/60,120/120,180/180,240/240,300/300} { \draw (B\i) -- (C\j); }
                            % labels
                            \node[above right] at ($(C60)!0.5!(B60)$) {$10$ cm};
                            \node[below] at ($(C240)!0.5!(C300)$) {$6$ cm};
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
                <p>
                    Work out, giving an exact answer in terms of <m>\sqrt{3}</m>, the following:
                </p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The area of one hexagonal face.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The total surface area of the prism.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            A regular hexagon can be split into six equilateral triangles of side <m>s</m>. Since the included angle is <m>60^\circ</m>, we have:
                            <md>
                                <mrow> A_{\text{triangle}} \amp = \frac{1}{2} ab \sin C </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \frac{1}{2} 6^2 \sin 60^\circ </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \frac{1}{2} 36 \times \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = 9\sqrt{3} </mrow>
                            </md>
                            
                            So the face area (the area of the hexagon) is six times the area of one triangle:
                            <me>
                                F = 6 \times 9\sqrt{3} = 54\sqrt{3} \, \text{cm}^2.
                            </me>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p> Perimeter of the hexagon is <m>P = 6s = 36 \, \text{cm}</m>. Lateral area = <m>P \times l = 36 \times 10 = 360 \, \text{cm}^2</m>.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Two faces = <m>2A = 2 \times 54\sqrt{3} = 108\sqrt{3} \, \text{cm}^2 \approx 187.06 \, \text{cm}^2</m>.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Total surface area = <m>2A + Pl = 108\sqrt{3} + 360 \, \text{cm}^2</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <title>A Harder Exercise</title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Two equilateral triangles with side lenghts <m>s</m> are connected by to form a prism of length <m>10\,\text{cm}^2</m>. Find an expression for the surface area in terms of <m>s</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <hint>
                <p>
                    Could Heron's formula be useful here?
                </p>
            </hint>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Let the side length be <m>s</m>. The face area is given by Heron's formula, with the semi-perimeter <m>S = \frac{3s}{2}</m>, and thus:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>F \amp = \sqrt{S(S-s)(S-s)(S-s)}</mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = \sqrt{\frac{3s}{2}\left(\frac{3s}{2}-s\right)^3}</mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = \sqrt{\frac{3s}{2}\left(\frac{s}{2}\right)^3}</mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = \sqrt{\frac{3s^4}{16}}</mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = \frac{s^2\sqrt{3}}{4}</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    The perimeter is <m>P = 3s</m>, so the lateral area is <m>Pl = 3s \times 10 = 30s</m>. The total surface area is thus:
                    <md> 
                        <mrow> \text{Surface Area} \amp = 2F + Pl </mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = 2 \times \frac{s^2\sqrt{3}}{4} + 30s</mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = \frac{s^2\sqrt{3}}{2} + 30s </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation</title>
        <table>
            <title>Differentiation Strategies</title>
            <tabular halign="left">
                <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Learner Group</cell>
                    <cell>Strategy &amp; Learning Experience</cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Struggling Learners (Support)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line><alert>Scaffolding:</alert> Provide pre-drawn nets with labelled dimensions. Use colour coding for different faces. Allow calculators for all calculations. Provide formula reference cards. Pair with peer tutors.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>On-Level Learners (Core)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line>The core lesson activities as described above.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Advanced Learners (Challenge)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line><alert>Extended Learning Experience:</alert> Design a box with specific surface area constraints. Find dimensions of a cuboid given its surface area and one dimension. Calculate surface area of classroom objects. Explore the relationship between surface area and volume.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Extension Activity</title>
            <p>
                <alert>Design Challenge:</alert> A company wants to design a rectangular gift box with a volume of <m>1000 \, \text{cm}^3</m>. Design three different boxes (with different dimensions) that all have this volume. Calculate the surface area of each design. Which design uses the least material (smallest surface area)? Explain why minimizing surface area is important for packaging companies.
            </p>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>
